          "kind": "thinking",
          "value": "The error is clear: `Unknown file extension \".ts\"` — the main process (Node.js) is trying to dynamically `import()` TypeScript files from the packages, but Node.js can't handle `.ts` files directly without a loader like `ts-node` or `tsx`. \n\nThe issue is in `main/index.ts` where we do:\n```ts\nconst { indexWorkspace } = await import('@infinity-canvas/ast-graph');\n```\n\nThe `@infinity-canvas/ast-graph` resolves to `packages/ast-graph/src/index.ts` — a TypeScript file. When electron-vite builds the main process, it compiles TS → JS and resolves these imports. But in dev mode with dynamic `import()`, Node.js tries to load the raw `.ts` file.\n\nThe fix: electron-vite's dev mode bundles the main process. But dynamic imports at runtime go through Node.js's module system, not through Vite's bundler. \n\nSolutions:\n1. Use static imports instead of dynamic `import()` — Vite will bundle them\n2. Or ensure the packages have a `main` field pointing to compiled JS, not `.ts`\n\nThe cleanest fix: change the dynamic `import()` in `main/index.ts` to static imports at the top of the file. This way electron-vite will bundle them during build/dev.\n\nLet me check the main process bundling setup.",
